node.text:
I think this year challenged everyone. In every way shape, or form. I think many of us wished 2020 looked differently.

It’s easy to look at the things that should have been, could have been & didn’t happen and let bitterness settle in, but I’m a firm believer that struggling is where we blossom and to not let our hearts grow cold in the storms.

So as I look back through my camera roll, there was so much smiling, new adventures and joy given the confines & chaos of 2020. Thank you @rachelveltriphoto for many of these memories engrained in my heart.

I’m going embrace the disappointments of 2020 while also celebrating the moments of joy entering into 2021. 

My theme for 2021 is to be “All In”, In everything I do and not hold back out of fear. To be more decisive and confident in myself, especially as a business woman.

@twenty2nutrition GIVEAWAY!!! 

What is your theme moving into 2021? 

To enter into our winter box giveaway launching tonight at 7pm EST like the post & tag a friend below and tell them something they did this year that was incredible along with your new theme moving into 2021!

node.text:
We go through phases and seasons of motivation.

Right now, my motivation has taken a hiatus. Getting back into training with everything going on, has been tough. Working out for the first time in my life, just isn’t a priority for me right now and that’s ok. I’ll swallow that tough pill.

I didn’t want to do this workout, but I knew my mental health needed it. Josh told me to go workout, he would pack packages.

So I turned off my brain, grabbed some dumbbells and went outside to workout in some sunshine.

It was exactly what I needed. To push myself until my lungs hurt. To break a sweat and to demolish the stress I was keeping inside.

You’re not going to always have motivation but what you can always have is the choice to do something you know that’s right for you even though you don’t want to. This is how discipline & consistency bloom.

Workout: sorry for the crappy filming, I didn’t intend on filming or posting this. 🙏🏼

10 reps of every exercise.

I broke it down into 2 circuits. Then finished with 4 minutes of ab core work on the ground. 3 rounds each circuit. 1 minute rest between circuits.

Happy Monday. I want to know what you do when your motivation takes a hike. This can be anything, not just fitness 🙌🏽

#10weekspostpartum

Especially in front of almost 1 million of you...

But it’s time to start normalizing postpartum depression and all it’s faucets of how it effect mothers, so they can stop struggling in silence and feel comfortable to speak up and get the help they need.

I shared my Postpartum struggles on my story a week or so ago because I’ve always been honest about my journey and this is no different, so why hide it?

 I had thousands & thousands of responses back of women in similar situations. Women who felt hopeless and alone or that something was wrong with them because everyone else appeared “happy” on IG or those around them.

I avoided posting it here because honestly the fear of people being cruel or saying it’s for “seeking attention” and all the other accusations & stigmas that cause women to stay silent during postpartum because I didn’t think I could mentally handle it.

Fuck that.

We do not need to be ashamed of our emotions. We do not need to be ashamed of where we are, we do not need to be ashamed of the struggles we are going through and we do NOT need to hide these feelings and be afraid to ask for help because of the stigma surrounding our struggles or the lack of understanding/education from others 👏🏼👏🏼

On my story is @drcassidy who specializes in PPD who was kind enough to talk about depression and how it can manifest & effect mothers differently. It will permanently be saved in my highlights to refer to or send to someone in need. There’s also many other accounts saved who are helpful too.

Mamas, You are not alone. You are worthy and you are so strong. There is no shame in getting help or opening up about how you feel. Your emotions are valid and real.♥️

Feel free to talk about your struggles below. It’s freeing 🙌🏽This is a safe place and I will delete all negativity.

A video of Jaden and myself getting adjusted☺️
.
.

Our entire family has been seeing @drmarcov since I was early pregnancy with Jaden. Without him, I wouldn’t have been able to stay active my first pregnancy due to SPD! He significantly helped make the spd pain manageable for me along with reducing back/hip pain. Jaden enjoys it too ☺️

Benefits for pregnancy:
👉🏻Find a REPUTABLE Chiropractor that specializes in Webster Technique. 

👉🏻 Webster Technique can help keep the pelvis balanced which can encourage baby to get in optimal position. The round ligaments take a beating during pregnancy and this technique can help keep them “happy” as I like to call it.

👉🏻 Reduces low back pain, sciatica relief, pelvic girdle pain and many other nagging aches & pains that can come with pregnancy.

👉🏻 Can help with indigestion
And so much more.

Not all chiropractors are created equal just like any profession. We’ve been seeing @drmarcov for over 3 years for a reason and will continue to. Baby will also be “adjusted” once born just like Jaden was when he was a newborn. Can help with breastfeeding too. Birth can be pretty traumatic on their little necks.

Chiropractic care isn’t for everyone, it definitely isn’t something that’s truly needed but it can make a world of a difference for many. I just wanted to share the things I’ve done during my pregnancy that have significantly helped me and give you tools to make decisions best for you🙏🏼
.
.

Of tearing & injury!

TAG A MAMA or friend ♥️ I’ll answer as many questions as I can.

There truly isn’t enough talk/eduction around pelvic floor and core health and it’s a shame because it is so important in women’s health.

The pelvic floor plays a vital role in pelvis stability, pregnancy/birth and postpartum journeys (why you guys see me harp on proper core engagement & breathing properly, pregnant or not)

My dear friend Kelley from @the.revelle and I have a small chit chat and scrape the surface about pelvic floor health & preparing the PF for delivery!🙌🏽

A few misconceptions we wanted to address based off what I asked on my stories!
 
👉🏻Kegels are NOT the “holy grail” exercise to strengthen your pelvic floor before/during pregnancy & postpartum.

👉🏻 In fact doing just kegels can worsen symptoms of incontinence, painful sex & prolapse because it creates overly tight pelvic floor muscles & they are often done WRONG.

👉🏻Kegels are not the “stopping of urine.” Please don’t do this to train your PF as it just focuses on the muscles surrounding the urinary sphincter & can create dysfunction. A correct Kegel is engaging the entire PF bed.

👉🏻 A strong balanced pelvic floor has the ability to engage & LENGTHEN with the same intensity.

👉🏻Preventative care is always the goal and can save you a lot of heart ache. The sooner you can create functionality in your core unit the better. This applies to ALL women (and men) but it Is NEVER to late to heal and restore your core.♥️

My core guide teaches in depth about core health, breathing and core engagement. Link in the bio.

I will always recommend seeing a reputable pelvic floor physio as routine checkups. It’s your health. It can make a world of a difference in your journeys where you are.🙌🏽

You can reach out to @the.revelle or go online to https://pelvicguru.com or https://aptaapps.apta.org//APTAPTDirectory/FindAPTDirectory.aspx to find someone in your area.

Prepping for vaginal delivery:
1. Perineal massage using hands & also the @kegelreleasecurve & epino are devices I’ll be using to help assist with that.
2. Lengthening the pelvic floor along with stretches shown in video!

A little over a year and a half ago we launched @twenty2nutrition in our home. Over the past year, we moved and were blessed to pack out of our garage and now here we are moving into our first warehouse! Feeling so unbelievably thankful.🙏🏼

Josh and I have poured our heart and soul into Twenty2 building it from the ground up. A two man team, with a lot of other obligations to manage on top of it.

Josh put in so many 80 hour weeks working full time at his other intensive job while also getting what needed to be done for Twenty2. A lot of 4am mornings and long long nights.

I learned to manage being a full time stay at home mom, run Twenty2 and manage all things business for “hannahbower2.”

We have finally reached a place where we can stop pumping the break and dive full force into our company and that feels so unbelievably good.😭🙌🏽

We couldn’t have done it without your belief and support in us, so thank you. We may not be the largest company out there, but we pack every order with love and truly care and are so proud of Twenty2 and what we stand for.

We are truly excited to see what the next year has in store for Twenty2. We have so many exciting things in the works for you guys🙌🏽

To honor and thank you guys! We’re giving away 3 $100 gift cards to @twenty2nutrition!

To ENTER:
1. Follow me & @twenty2nutrition 
2. Comment something positive or your favorite Twenty2 product to a friend!
Dattsssss it! 🥰

Getting baby in optimal position! 🙌🏽- TAG a mama!

As you guys know this lil baby was breech at my 32 week ultra sound. Seems this baby and Jaden are already bonding. 😂 Yesterday, I was able to see my massage body worker and we successfully were able to turn baby to head down 🙏🏼

Today, I saw my wonderful doula to reiterate and encourage baby’s head down position and this is what we did and my “homework” everyday until birth. I thought I would share all of what I’ve done♥️

All of these positions help open the pelvis and the shifting from side to side can help baby get in the best position for birth which is LOA. ( left occiput anterior)- check out spinning babies for more info. 😊

Side lying release- really important you are straight. You will need someone to assist you.

In addition to these I also have been doing: ( posted in flipping baby highlight)
1. Pelvic floor work- perineal massage. Prone to a hypertonic PF.- super important for birth.
2. Stability work in my pelvis as I’m also prone to instability.
3. 💥Inversions- both handstand style and lying down coupled with side lying release, rebozo & massage. ( not shown- this was huge yesterday in flipping this angel)
4. Fascia & massage work
5. Ball swivels

If you’re in the Denver area would 100% recommend both of these ladies.🖤
* My Doula- Donna Rigert 
* Harmony’s Family Cooperative- Regina

node.text:
I literally was going from one exercise to the next before this and not feeling motivated...at all. Had no intentions of filming my workout tonight. But here we are! LIVE workout to follow along. Grab some music. Let’s do this.

Typically when I feel this way I know I need to spike my heart rate to get some happy endorphins going. So I tend to do mini MIIT ( medium intensity interval training) because I wouldn’t necessarily call this hiiit buttttt the feeling after is worttthhhhh it. 👏🏼.
.

Broke a sweat, got some happy feelings and got SOMETHING IN.

A bad workout is better than no workout. Any movement is better than nothing ♥️ You can add weight, resistance and maybe so more plyos to the reverse lunges to make it HIIT!

Workout: 10 minutes
20 gate swings
20 reverse lunges- half way through I switched to forward lunges
10-12 pikes peak push-up
REST 10-20seconds

Modify the pikes peak pushups if you are coning or don’t have proper form. Just go on knees!

#20weekspregnant

Let’s gooooooo, FAM! #sweatisgold. All you need is yourself and a little extra push to get out and move your body. Turn off your brain and go.🙌🏽
.
.
It’s absolutely ok to lack or have ZERO motivation during this time. It’s ok to gain weight or even lose strength. You have all the time to get back after it when this is all over. 🖤 please, don’t be too hard on yourself. Extend yourself grace. This is a really weird time. “Muscle memory” truly is a thing and your progress will not be completely lost or lost at all.🙏🏼
.
.
You also don’t need equipment or a home gym to keep healthy. Your body itself and nature is your own gym! 🙌🏽
.
.
For this workout I ran .75 mile. Stopped, did about 15 minutes of the following exercises than ran back.

No reps or sets. Go until you can’t any longer on an exercise and switch immediately to something else!

Just get your body moving. Endorphins flowing. You’ll feel better.

We also go to see baby today! Looks just like Jaden 🥺 #13weekspregnant

node.text:
Some of my favorite workouts are 10-15min HIIT or interval circuit sessions.

When I’m on a crunch for time HIIT & interval training is 9/10x what my go to workout will be.

1. It makes me feel good. 
2. It gets endorphins going!! This feeling is the absolute best.
3. I tend to break a good sweat and feel accomplished.
4. It’s good for my ♥️ health
5. My muscles feel on fire and call me crazy, but I crave that feeling. 🤣

There is some slight differences in wanted to talk about HIIT vs Interval training as they often are lumped as the same thing. They technically aren’t the same!

When doing HIIT it’s important to pick an exercise that will max your body out for the time allotted. Typically 15-45sec intervals. 30 seconds is the standard.

True HIIT allows your heart to recover back down to baseline. Then repeat.

Interval training doesn’t completely allow your heart rate to return back to normal and is found in trainings like AMRAPS, TABATAS & Circuits.

No longer than 30 minutes is necessary for a true HIIT session.

Interval training really doesn’t have a time constraint!

The workout shown, can be done both ways :)— however I did it as an interval session!

Happy Thursday 🥰 this full
Body interval workout is up on the app!

node.text:
A little story through photos. From middle school to present.🥰

Growing up as an athlete I was I was always pretty fit. When I hit puberty at 16, my hormones went pretty crazy. I went from an 80lb 4’8 freshman to a 130lb 5’4” sophomore. It was a big hurdle for me as I also wasn’t performing at my best and it was just the start of health issues. The dieting and disordered behaviors started my junior year of high school and were exponentially exasperated in college. The pressure to look a certain way was so engrained in me as a gymnast.

I then had a career ending injury followed by some other traumatic life experiences including sexual assault that spiraled me into a really dark & broken place. Check out the @wegotherepodcast

We all have our own journeys.

Our own beginnings. Our own demons.

And what’s most important is that you don’t put a start and finish line on your journey.

Your life isn’t a race♥️

Lifestyles take time. I’ve been learning about myself, my body, what feels good, what makes me happy and what works for me since I was 15 years old.

My lifestyle definitely didn’t happen overnight or even a few weeks or a year. YEARS.

I found happiness and contentment within myself while dating josh! ( not because of him) but that’s when my fitness journey, self worth & healing really began blossoming!

Be patient with yourself. Baby stops and little changes lead to bigger changes. Both mentally, emotionally & physically.

The recipe: time, commitment & consistency ♥️

Let me preface this by saying I don’t believe in demonizing any kind of exercise. If it makes you happy, feels good and keeps you moving your body, it’s an A+ movement for me.

However, different exercises may have better outcomes for you if you have *specific* goals.

Growing your booty has been an area that many individuals focus on! With that, there is countless advice all across the board on what said person did to achieve their glutes and it may not lead to the same results for you.

Often it’s exercises like the first two shown.

Although these exercises can work the glutes, they aren’t ideal for hypertrophy.

These are my favorite exercises (not all) that are a better choice to implement if glute growth is a goal!

1. Hip thrusts/ glute bridge variations
2. Reverse lunges or step ups
3. Rounded back extensions
4. Deadlifts & RDLs 
5. Cable side kick backs for glute medius

As always progressive overload, muscle tension and adequate nutrition (sleep + recovery too) are also really important for hypertrophy! ♥️

A good ol dumbbell only upper body day! 🥰 There was a time, I hated doing upper body. 

I felt like I wasn’t working out “hard enough” or wasn’t getting in a good workout because I wasn’t gasping for air the entire workout. 😅

I also believed that I’d bulk way too easily if I lifted heavier.🙃

Truth is, I wish I could tell my younger self that more isn’t always better. You don’t have to kill yourself or be completely exhausted after a workout for it to be “good” or beneficial for you and that lifting heavier was actually the best way to accomplish the goals I had for myself! 

I now enjoy upper body days 😋 what’s your favorite muscle to work?

This workout along with a few others went up on the app! Link in bio. 🙏🏼

node.text:
I am honestly so shocked but so unbelievably happy!

When I learned this hex bar was 55lbs and not 35lbs…

I squealed haha as I lifted more than I thought I had. 235lbs!

This is the heaviest I’ve ever lifted and I did it for 4 reps. (Shows sometimes our bodies can lift more than what we think we can)

 I always give myself at least a YEAR to really feel normal again or have expectations of feeling myself or “back to where I was” pre-pregnancy fitness wise. Birthing humans is hard work and takes a toll on the body and honoring it is important postpartum! 

So having this PR on a day I didn’t want to go or have any motivation was just such beautiful surprise yesterday.

I’m proud of myself 🙏🏼 

I think we all can fall into the mindset trap of “why bother going if I don’t feel like it, don’t have motivation or feel blah”…

But there’s so much more that can come from “deciding to just go” than a possible PR or an incredible workout…

1. Showing up for yourself even when circumstances aren’t ideal.— this is HUGE.
2. This leads to consistency. Consistency = results.
3. Spark new motivation 
4. It all adds up! Even if it’s a bad workout, any movement should still be celebrated. Small changes over time lead to big outcomes.

I shared the workout I did today on my app! Start for $1 month trial. link in bio.🥰

Correct form for Lat Pull downs! 🙌🏽 let me know if this is helpful.

Remember every person in the gym goes through a learning phase! Practice is what improves form, keep at it.

Lats primarily work the “Upper Back” so if your goal is lower lats or lower back muscles there’s better exercises to do.

Things to keep mindful of:
👉🏻 Weight: if you’re having to compensate by really rocking backward to pull, it’s too heavy. ( yes, There are some advanced lifters that this may be ok for, but for the general pop..not necessary)
👉🏻 Pulling forward with a rounded spine or “crunch” movement- lacks scapula engagement.
👉🏻 too much back lean or torso movement as you pull

Good Cues:
👍🏼 Pull Bar Apart first then…
👍🏼Squeeze elbows behind ribs at the end of rep
👍🏼Exhale & Engage core as you pull
👍🏼Puff chest up towards ceiling or slight extension of the upper back
👍🏼minimal body movement!
👍🏼 Slow motion on the way back- keeps you from losing engagement

Hope you found this helpful! 🙏🏼

node.text:
One of the biggest insecurities I had growing up was my athletic build.

It was often a joke at my expense that I looked like a little boy in high school at 16 years old.

I was small. I had no hips. Lacked curves…Boobs? Ha! “You have mosquito bites.”

And although I laughed and joked with it…It perpetuated my intense insecurities growing up of just wanting to be wanted. ( I touched on this in my story with @wegotherepodcast )

No guys liked me because I wasn’t “woman” enough or beautiful enough like, “insert beautiful person”

The comparison game. Oh how I would learn that comparison is the thief of joy.

Took me a long time to realize that wanting someone else’s body, even if I did everything they did, would never structurally change what god gave me and most importantly would never make me happy….or confident.

Not to say that I didn’t use ppl as inspiration, I did…but I shifted my motivation from wanting to look like them to wanting to work hard like they did & learning the knowledge they had & the mindset they focused on.

I slowly learned to celebrate my own gifts. My own shape. My own life. A new appreciation and outlook began towards myself. And my fitness journey took off.

It didn’t happen over night. Balance didn’t happen for a while. Ive been at this lifestyle journey now for over 14 years. But I kept learning about myself, what worked for me & what didn’t.

If your goals are solely based on looking like someone or “I’ll be happy when…” I just encourage you to maybe shift your goals and mindset to celebrate your own uniqueness rather than pit yourself against something that only leads to discouragement ♥️

FULL BODY🔥| Functional circuit with modifications below.🙌🏽
This was such a fun little circuit. I know body weight work & barbell work can be hard to incorporate and maybe intimidating....but we all start from somewhere. Start small, you will get better if you’re consistent🙏🏼

•••WORKOUT:•••
Shoot for little to no rest between each exercise. Rest 3-5 min after each round.

🍓Deficit Deads- increased range of motion = more tension. This is a way of progressive overloading your lifts.
🍊 Modify and use dumbbells or regular dead
🍓Resistance Band SRDL- there is no reason for the elevation other than allowing more tension in the band
🍊 Modify-no band or use DB.
🍓V-up to Pistol- don’t allow knee to cave in as you stand.
🍊Modify and stand with both feet. Bend knees in v up if you can’t regulate IAP( coning or rounding)- or opt for the shot gun ab crunches shown.
🍓Alternating deficit push-up
🍊 modify and do push-ups or kneeling pushups
🍓Elevated Glute Bridge- slow & controlled. These are not meant to be explosive like a thrust.
🍊modify- Use straight bar or DB
🍓Tucked wipers & tuck ups- alternate these two exercises between rounds. Make sure to engage the core before lifting legs. This helps with not swinging and regulating IAP.
🍊modify and just hang squeezing all of your muscles as tight as you can or use less range of motion. (Shown)
